00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:42.732
Well, Brad and I are both big
science outreach advocates.

00:02:42.732 --> 00:02:44.440
And one of the things
we're interested in

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:48.370
is trying to get general
audiences more engaged

00:02:48.370 --> 00:02:50.950
with basic science information.

00:02:50.950 --> 00:02:53.120
By and large, the way
the broader public

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:57.080
gets science is filtered through
types of media sources that

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:00.770
try to spin and make big
mountains out of small mole

00:03:00.770 --> 00:03:01.562
hills.

00:03:01.562 --> 00:03:02.770
And often, it gets distorted.

00:03:02.770 --> 00:03:05.930
So we need to get the
general public more engaged

00:03:05.930 --> 00:03:08.465
in the real core
scientific literature.

00:03:08.465 --> 00:03:10.590
So we've thought about
possibilities of doing this.

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:13.580
One, we thought about using
internet memes as our figures

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:15.040
to illustrate our findings.

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:18.510
So use your LOL Cat to
display Hebbian networks.

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:20.900
That didn't go over so well.

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:23.940
We pondered, accidentally,
