00:46:26.110 --> 00:46:27.630
TIMOTHY VERSTYNEN: Yeah.

00:46:27.630 --> 00:46:29.590
The we're all infected
and we're just going

00:46:29.590 --> 00:46:32.180
to reanimate when whenever we--

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:32.930
AUDIENCE: Romero--

00:46:32.930 --> 00:46:34.840
TIMOTHY VERSTYNEN:
--transition from one state.

00:46:34.840 --> 00:46:36.800
Romero was-- so we actually
got to interview George Romero.

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:38.133
And we were asking him about it.

00:46:38.133 --> 00:46:40.130
He said, the way he
made up, particularly

00:46:40.130 --> 00:46:43.732
in his first three movies,
he didn't care about it.

00:46:43.732 --> 00:46:45.690
He was trying to use the
zombies as a metaphor.

00:46:45.690 --> 00:46:47.850
So in the first one,
he kept it vague.

00:46:47.850 --> 00:46:52.994
There was the satellite from
outer space that had come back.

00:46:52.994 --> 00:46:54.410
And it was somehow
linked to that.

00:46:54.410 --> 00:46:56.097
But it could have
been space radiation.

00:46:56.097 --> 00:46:57.680
And he was saying
he explicitly didn't

00:46:57.680 --> 00:47:00.090
care about what caused it.

00:47:00.090 --> 00:47:02.440
He just wanted them to be there.

00:47:02.440 --> 00:47:07.034
In fact, he put the nail
in our coffin of our theory

00:47:07.034 --> 00:47:07.950
about zombie movement.

00:47:07.950 --> 00:47:10.980
But I'll tell you
about that later.

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:13.361
So I think what happened
was because the early zombie

00:47:13.361 --> 00:47:15.360
cultures didn't really
care about the mechanism,

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:17.784
there was lots of
different explanations.

00:47:17.784 --> 00:47:19.450
From a biological
standpoint, it doesn't

00:47:19.450 --> 00:47:23.270
seem like that
would be the case.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:27.206
So I like the idea of the
infection theory of zombieism.

00:47:27.206 --> 00:47:28.372
AUDIENCE: So like a latent--

00:47:28.372 --> 00:47:30.100
TIMOTHY VERSTYNEN: Yeah.

00:47:30.100 --> 00:47:33.840
The real phenomenon that I think
fascinates me the most in this

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:35.930
is toxoplasmosis.

00:47:35.930 --> 00:47:38.130
So toxoplasmosis is a
single cell organism.

00:47:38.130 --> 00:47:39.435
It's what lives in cat poop.

00:47:39.435 --> 00:47:42.450
And it's why pregnant women
shouldn't be around cat poop.

00:47:42.450 --> 00:47:45.370
It's because it induces
flu-like symptoms

00:47:45.370 --> 00:47:46.740
if you get the infection.

00:47:46.740 --> 00:47:50.780
And it'd be dangerous to
fetuses and young children.

00:47:50.780 --> 00:47:53.070
But normally, if you're
an adult and you get it,

00:47:53.070 --> 00:47:53.960
you just get a flu.

00:47:53.960 --> 00:47:54.930
It seems to go away.

00:47:54.930 --> 00:47:58.500
But really what happens is
it's a single organism that

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:01.955
reproduces sexually in
the gut of a feline.

00:48:01.955 --> 00:48:04.080
So that's where it gets
its most genetic diversity.

00:48:04.080 --> 00:48:07.990
When it's outside the feline,
it can only reproduce asexually.

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:09.680
So it clones itself.

00:48:09.680 --> 00:48:12.240
So what this organism does
is even after the infection,

00:48:12.240 --> 00:48:14.530
it stays latent in your system.

00:48:14.530 --> 00:48:17.530
And in the mammals
that it infects,

00:48:17.530 --> 00:48:20.720
so the rodents,
humans, it actually

00:48:20.720 --> 00:48:24.470
starts modifying the
neuropharmacology

00:48:24.470 --> 00:48:26.100
of the individual's brain.

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:29.090
And what you see is you see
characteristic behavioral

00:48:29.090 --> 00:48:32.035
differences in people who have
had toxoplasmosis assistant

00:48:32.035 --> 00:48:34.900
and survived versus
those who don't.

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:36.670
And the most
classic case of this

00:48:36.670 --> 00:48:38.180
was an experimental
study where they

00:48:38.180 --> 00:48:41.010
took a rat-- and rats
normally hate cats.

00:48:41.010 --> 00:48:43.216
They're instinctively
afraid of cats-- gave it

00:48:43.216 --> 00:48:45.410
a toxoplasmosis intervention.

00:48:45.410 --> 00:48:48.140
And across time, if
you had a glass wall

00:48:48.140 --> 00:48:52.180
between the rat and the cat,
normally the rat's over here.

00:48:52.180 --> 00:48:54.290
But as the infection
rate occurs,

00:48:54.290 --> 00:48:55.930
the rat actually
starts to not only

00:48:55.930 --> 00:48:59.090
not be afraid, but want
to be near the cat.

00:48:59.090 --> 00:49:02.130
So there's increased
risk taking behavior

00:49:02.130 --> 00:49:04.110
that happens as a
result of the infection.

00:49:04.110 --> 00:49:06.909
And actually, that same kind
of behavior, not towards cats

00:49:06.909 --> 00:49:08.575
obviously, but more
risk taking behavior

00:49:08.575 --> 00:49:10.390
is seen in individual
human individuals

00:49:10.390 --> 00:49:11.530
who've had the infection.

00:49:11.530 --> 00:49:13.630
So somehow, the
single cell organism

00:49:13.630 --> 00:49:16.360
is hijacking the
complex circuits that

00:49:16.360 --> 00:49:19.060
induce our ability to be
afraid of certain things

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:20.630
and it increased risk taking.

00:49:20.630 --> 00:49:24.260
So that coupled with the
popularization of the infection

00:49:24.260 --> 00:49:26.890
theory of zombies is the
more interesting link there.

00:49:26.890 --> 00:49:29.860
And if you're going to ask me
about biologically plausible,

00:49:29.860 --> 00:49:33.312
with the caveat that it's
still way, way far away,

00:49:33.312 --> 00:49:35.895
that is more the route that you
would see something like this.

00:49:35.895 --> 00:49:36.226
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:49:36.226 --> 00:49:38.100
This is more than the
rat simply becoming

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:39.790
acclimated to having a cat on
the other side of the wall.

00:49:39.790 --> 00:49:40.410
TIMOTHY VERSTYNEN: Yeah.

00:49:40.410 --> 00:49:42.050
So you don't see
it all in rats that

00:49:42.050 --> 00:49:43.383
have never exposed to the virus.

00:49:43.383 --> 00:49:46.110
They stay far away.

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:46.610
Yeah.

